1
00:00:10,219 --> 00:00:12,638
[ticking]

2
00:00:16,015 --> 00:00:17,518
[dings]

3
00:00:22,064 --> 00:00:23,815
[radio static]

4
00:00:34,326 --> 00:00:36,078
[ticking]

5
00:00:55,973 --> 00:00:56,974
[sighs]

6
00:00:58,934 --> 00:01:00,394
[ticking continues]

7
00:01:06,233 --> 00:01:07,860
[dings]

8
00:01:26,295 --> 00:01:27,838
[sighs]

9
00:01:36,471 --> 00:01:38,223
[ticking]

10
00:01:47,983 --> 00:01:49,860
[flies buzzing]

11
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:49,419
[dings]

12
00:02:51,255 --> 00:02:53,006
[engine rumbles]

13
00:03:48,353 --> 00:03:49,354
[horn honks]

14
00:05:29,204 --> 00:05:33,959
To all of our customers: Management was obligated to open your units.

15
00:05:34,042 --> 00:05:36,712
Restitution will be made.
Apologies.

16
00:06:28,222 --> 00:06:29,223
[sniffs]

17
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:31,785
[phone rings]

18
00:07:31,869 --> 00:07:33,537
[sighs]

19
00:07:47,509 --> 00:07:49,511
[ringing continues]

20
00:07:52,181 --> 00:07:53,932
[sighs]

21
00:07:55,934 --> 00:07:57,311
[ringing stops]

22
00:08:10,949 --> 00:08:12,993
[phone rings]

23
00:08:22,961 --> 00:08:24,838
[Carol] Uh… Hola, señor.

24
00:08:26,048 --> 00:08:27,174
Me llamo--

25
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:47,194
[phone rings]

26
00:09:00,874 --> 00:09:03,418
Hola, yo soy Carol Sturka.

27
00:09:03,502 --> 00:09:09,424
Uh, estoy de los…
[clears throat] …United States-- [in Spanish] Leave me alone, you sons of bitches!

28
00:09:28,819 --> 00:09:30,737
[phone rings]

29
00:09:35,492 --> 00:09:37,995
[Carol] Fuck your mother, asshole!

30
00:09:38,078 --> 00:09:39,705
[bashing phone]

31
00:10:14,364 --> 00:10:16,366
[theme song playing]

32
00:11:02,329 --> 00:11:03,622
[sighs]

33
00:11:24,059 --> 00:11:25,435
[engine starts]

34
00:11:25,519 --> 00:11:27,604
["Genie in a Bottle" plays on radio]

35
00:11:37,865 --> 00:11:39,449
[engine dies]

36
00:11:45,122 --> 00:11:46,123
[sighs]

37
00:12:01,555 --> 00:12:03,056
[other, in English] Hi, Carol.

38
00:12:05,559 --> 00:12:06,977
Can you hear us?

39
00:12:09,938 --> 00:12:16,570
If you feel like responding, all you have to do is pick up the handset and speak into it.

40
00:12:19,281 --> 00:12:21,366
It's got a push-to-talk button
on the side.

41
00:12:21,450 --> 00:12:22,534
[others] Hey, Carol!

42
00:12:22,618 --> 00:12:26,663
[other] Works just like on Adam-12.
Remember how you used to love that show?

43
00:12:26,747 --> 00:12:27,748
What?

44
00:12:27,831 --> 00:12:30,083
[other] Oh, hi, Carol.

45
00:12:30,167 --> 00:12:34,004
You left the hospital kind of quickly.
Is, uh, everything okay?

46
00:12:34,087 --> 00:12:36,465
- Yep. Yes.
- [others] Hey, Carol!

47
00:12:36,548 --> 00:12:39,218
[Carol] Just… Just headed home.

48
00:12:40,093 --> 00:12:43,096
[other] Would you be more comfortable
in your Range Rover?

49
00:12:43,180 --> 00:12:44,723
We can deliver it to you.

50
00:12:45,516 --> 00:12:49,186
Also, we're happy to remove
the alcohol interlock device.

51
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:50,270
No.

52
00:13:06,370 --> 00:13:07,788
[others] Hey, Carol.

53
00:13:09,665 --> 00:13:10,874
What are you doing here?

54
00:13:12,417 --> 00:13:16,547
You're in my house? What the hell
are you doing inside my house?

55
00:13:16,630 --> 00:13:17,840
Patching shrapnel holes.

56
00:13:17,923 --> 00:13:20,384
Plus, there was a lot of broken glass
to clean up.

57
00:13:20,467 --> 00:13:23,428
Well, who gave you permission
to be in my house?

58
00:13:23,512 --> 00:13:24,930
You did.

59
00:13:25,013 --> 00:13:30,519
Remember? When you were riding with us
in the ambulance and we were applying a pressure bandage to Zosia's back.

60
00:13:30,602 --> 00:13:35,566
And we asked you if you'd like us
to tidy up your house a little bit and you sort of nodded absently.

61
00:13:35,649 --> 00:13:38,986
Okay. Jesus, fine. Whatever.
Is everyone out now?

62
00:13:39,069 --> 00:13:41,738
Yes. And we're almost done here, Carol.

63
00:13:41,822 --> 00:13:45,909
But we could leave the finishing touches
for later and clear out now if you'd like.

64
00:13:45,993 --> 00:13:47,077
Give you some space.

65
00:13:49,329 --> 00:13:50,330
Do I know you?

66
00:13:50,956 --> 00:13:51,957
Hi.

67
00:13:54,585 --> 00:13:56,044
You're the fucking mayor.

68
00:13:56,879 --> 00:13:58,088
Thank you for your vote.

69
00:15:18,794 --> 00:15:20,295
[door opens]

70
00:15:22,130 --> 00:15:23,841
[Carol] I need a volunteer.

71
00:15:23,924 --> 00:15:25,843
Not a politician.

72
00:15:28,470 --> 00:15:30,222
You. Shorty.

73
00:15:30,305 --> 00:15:33,767
Rest of you just take a… coffee break,
or whatever floats your boat.

74
00:15:33,851 --> 00:15:35,394
Come with me.

75
00:15:35,477 --> 00:15:36,478
Happy to.

76
00:15:43,360 --> 00:15:46,321
[sighs] Have a seat, uh… What's your name?

77
00:15:47,781 --> 00:15:49,032
Your name?

78
00:15:49,783 --> 00:15:55,455
Uh, well… This individual went by Lawrence J. Kless.

79
00:15:55,539 --> 00:15:59,084
Or Larry to his friends,
of which he had many.

80
00:15:59,168 --> 00:16:01,044
Whatever. Just… have a seat.

81
00:16:04,214 --> 00:16:05,757
[Carol clears throat]

82
00:16:11,555 --> 00:16:13,348
Do you like my books?

83
00:16:13,432 --> 00:16:15,392
Oh, we love your books.

84
00:16:15,475 --> 00:16:17,102
What do you love about them?

85
00:16:17,186 --> 00:16:21,940
Everything. Your books are an expression
of you. And we love you.

86
00:16:22,024 --> 00:16:27,863
Mmm. Need you to be more specific.
Character arcs. Plot turns.

87
00:16:27,946 --> 00:16:31,783
Oh, yes. Yes. We love the character arcs
and the plot turns.

88
00:16:32,701 --> 00:16:34,161
Which ones?

89
00:16:34,244 --> 00:16:35,412
All of them.

90
00:16:37,247 --> 00:16:40,751
No offense, Larry, but, uh,
I think you're bullshitting me.

91
00:16:40,834 --> 00:16:43,629
Sounds to me like you haven't even
actually read my work.

92
00:16:44,588 --> 00:16:47,216
Oh. But we have.

93
00:16:48,717 --> 00:16:50,385
Gosh, where do we even begin?

94
00:16:51,553 --> 00:16:57,601
In your first novel, uh, we greatly admire the description of Lucasia's gown on page two.

95
00:16:58,852 --> 00:17:09,988
"Gossamer threads of the finest shang silk
shimmered like spun gold, as if the sun itself were showering Lucasia's shoulders with resplendent kisses."

96
00:17:12,281 --> 00:17:13,867
That made quite a few of us tingle.

97
00:17:14,952 --> 00:17:16,828
Okay.

98
00:17:19,873 --> 00:17:20,874
Ha.

99
00:17:24,752 --> 00:17:30,467
How would you say
my work compares to… Shakespeare?

100
00:17:30,551 --> 00:17:33,595
Equally. Equally wonderful.

101
00:17:33,679 --> 00:17:39,476
You love my books as much as… Macbeth?

102
00:17:40,018 --> 00:17:41,270
Or Much Ado?

103
00:17:41,353 --> 00:17:44,982
Yes. And Henry VI, parts one, two
and three.

104
00:17:45,065 --> 00:17:48,569
Well, I mean, what about a crowd-pleaser?
Romeo and Juliet?

105
00:17:48,652 --> 00:17:52,614
Wonderful. Have you read
the first quarto of 1597?

106
00:17:52,698 --> 00:17:56,243
No, you haven't, but you must.
We'll bring you the original.

107
00:17:56,326 --> 00:18:05,335
So, Larry, you are telling me that
you love the Wycaro series as much as the most famous English language play of all time?

108
00:18:05,419 --> 00:18:06,795
Carol.

109
00:18:07,421 --> 00:18:11,383
When we think about a passage
from one of your wonderful-- Stop using that word.

110
00:18:13,010 --> 00:18:14,386
From one of your books.

111
00:18:15,429 --> 00:18:19,933
We experience it through many eyes.
Many hearts.

112
00:18:21,018 --> 00:18:23,312
Do you remember a woman named
Moira McAllister?

113
00:18:24,021 --> 00:18:28,567
Uh, crazy Moira from Kansas City
that sends me these dumb crocheted hats?

114
00:18:29,693 --> 00:18:31,904
Right, of course. She's one of you now.

115
00:18:32,529 --> 00:18:34,239
- Yes.
- Mmm.

116
00:18:34,323 --> 00:18:38,911
Before she found your books,
Moira was deeply depressed.

117
00:18:40,120 --> 00:18:46,919
In fact, she was going to… You gave her something to live for.

118
00:18:47,002 --> 00:18:48,795
You made her life better.

119
00:18:49,922 --> 00:18:54,468
That's how we see your work, and you.
Through Moira's eyes.

120
00:18:59,556 --> 00:19:01,183
What did Helen think of my books?

121
00:19:05,896 --> 00:19:07,356
Tell me.

122
00:19:07,439 --> 00:19:09,608
Helen loved you very much.

123
00:19:09,691 --> 00:19:11,109
Not what I asked, Larry.

124
00:19:13,278 --> 00:19:16,907
Spit it out. What did Helen
think of the Wycaro books?

125
00:19:17,616 --> 00:19:20,911
Carol, you expressly told us
that Helen is off-limits.

126
00:19:20,994 --> 00:19:24,331
Yeah, but you know what?
Special dispensation this one time.

127
00:19:24,414 --> 00:19:27,960
What did Helen think of my Wycaro books?

128
00:19:31,004 --> 00:19:32,005
Larry?

129
00:19:32,798 --> 00:19:36,051
She thought they were… harmless.

130
00:19:39,388 --> 00:19:40,639
Harmless?

131
00:19:43,475 --> 00:19:46,687
"Cotton candy" was the phrase
she used in her mind. Mostly.

132
00:19:46,770 --> 00:19:47,980
Cotton candy.

133
00:19:48,897 --> 00:19:50,232
Yes.

134
00:19:50,315 --> 00:19:53,652
And as you know, Helen loved cotton candy.

135
00:19:53,735 --> 00:19:56,572
I don't actually recall Helen
ever eating cotton candy.

136
00:19:56,655 --> 00:20:12,629
Oh, no. She consumed it four times
in her life, and each ti… Yeah. You weren't there. [chuckles] But really… Helen thought you knew how to please your audience.

137
00:20:13,505 --> 00:20:18,135
And she was so grateful for
the beautiful life the two of you shared, that Wycaro provided.

138
00:20:19,011 --> 00:20:20,554
She was so proud of you.

139
00:20:21,180 --> 00:20:23,891
What did Helen think
of my unpublished novel?

140
00:20:24,683 --> 00:20:27,186
Mmm. Bitter Chrysalis.

141
00:20:29,646 --> 00:20:31,023
What did she think?

142
00:20:37,362 --> 00:20:42,492
Carol. This line of inquiry isn't…
[chuckles] - Can we talk about something else? - I wanna know.

143
00:20:45,078 --> 00:20:47,206
If you tell me, it'll make me happy.

144
00:20:57,007 --> 00:20:58,592
Helen thought it was fine.

145
00:20:59,927 --> 00:21:02,304
Fine as in good?

146
00:21:03,680 --> 00:21:07,976
Or fine as in… "meh"?

147
00:21:09,728 --> 00:21:10,729
Yeah, "meh."

148
00:21:10,812 --> 00:21:13,690
[stammers] What about the last 200 pages?

149
00:21:14,608 --> 00:21:18,028
[stammers] Helen stopped on page 137,
paragraph three.

150
00:21:19,029 --> 00:21:21,615
It's 489 pages long.

151
00:21:21,698 --> 00:21:24,493
She read the last two pages.
Thought it wrapped up nice.

152
00:21:24,576 --> 00:21:27,454
- [stammers] If she hated it so much…
- She didn't hate it.

153
00:21:27,538 --> 00:21:30,582
[stammers] If she hated it so much,
why did she tell me to publish it?

154
00:21:30,666 --> 00:21:34,753
Because she talked to Val, and they agreed
that it wouldn't hurt your career.

155
00:21:34,837 --> 00:21:36,463
And it would make you happy.

156
00:21:42,511 --> 00:21:43,512
Out.

157
00:22:46,116 --> 00:22:47,284
Hi, Carol.

158
00:22:52,998 --> 00:22:54,917
[Zosia sighs]

159
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:56,418
[Carol] Here.

160
00:23:01,131 --> 00:23:02,132
Thank you.

161
00:23:02,841 --> 00:23:14,937
- You want this?
- [chuckles] Do you like your police car?

162
00:23:16,104 --> 00:23:17,564
Sure.

163
00:23:17,648 --> 00:23:26,406
Fun fact, the police officer who drove that vehicle, his son's third-grade teacher's husband's sister was a chartered member of the Wycaro fan club.

164
00:23:26,490 --> 00:23:28,242
Wow. Chills.

165
00:23:33,080 --> 00:23:35,249
Uh, listen, about the, um…

166
00:23:37,334 --> 00:23:38,627
[mimics explosion]

167
00:23:39,211 --> 00:23:51,473
It wouldn't have happened if I had had
the foresight to understand that you people are… generous enough to give me actual explosives, and I regret it.

168
00:23:51,557 --> 00:23:52,724
Please don't.

169
00:23:52,808 --> 00:23:54,768
Well, I'm s-sorry you got hurt.

170
00:23:59,690 --> 00:24:02,401
Are you up for answering some questions?

171
00:24:04,653 --> 00:24:06,029
Certainly.

172
00:24:10,450 --> 00:24:18,250
Uh, about a week ago,
the Undersecretary of Ag… Well, I mean you. I know you're all one. I get the basics.

173
00:24:18,333 --> 00:24:22,087
Anyway, all of you,
in the form of the Undersecretary of…

174
00:24:22,171 --> 00:24:23,630
[sighs, chuckles]

175
00:24:24,798 --> 00:24:29,344
You told me that you don't
really understand how all this works.

176
00:24:29,428 --> 00:24:34,766
This joining. So my question is,
do you understand it now?

177
00:24:36,059 --> 00:24:38,979
We have quite a bit more insight
into it now, yes.

178
00:24:39,062 --> 00:24:43,942
So… Is there a way to reverse it?

179
00:24:45,319 --> 00:24:46,528
The joining?

180
00:24:54,286 --> 00:24:56,496
Is there not a way to reverse it?

181
00:24:59,666 --> 00:25:00,667
Zosia?

182
00:25:00,751 --> 00:25:06,757
We want so much to please you,
Carol, but we… we can't answer questions like that.

183
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:11,053
Right. Except your nonanswer is my answer.

184
00:25:12,429 --> 00:25:17,518
'Cause I don't think you can lie to me.
I don't think it's something you can do.

185
00:25:18,101 --> 00:25:21,355
But you would definitely tell me
if the answer was no.

186
00:25:23,815 --> 00:25:26,944
- We're sorry you're so troubled by this.
- Do I seem troubled?

187
00:25:28,487 --> 00:25:30,113
This is me happy.

188
00:25:31,114 --> 00:25:33,116
I mean, congratulations. You did it.

189
00:25:35,452 --> 00:25:37,829
Soon enough you'll understand everything.

190
00:25:39,373 --> 00:25:41,291
And you will feel so much better.

191
00:25:44,628 --> 00:25:46,088
Freedom Falls.

192
00:25:50,592 --> 00:25:52,386
You know what that means, don't you?

193
00:25:53,804 --> 00:25:55,931
Of course you do. You know everything.

194
00:25:56,014 --> 00:25:59,393
Tell me about it. Tell me
about Camp fucking Freedom Falls.

195
00:26:07,025 --> 00:26:14,032
You were sixteen. Beginning to understand
yourself. And your mother, she sent… Yeah, go on. What'd she do?

196
00:26:15,868 --> 00:26:21,248
She sent you to… [sighs] …a conversion
therapy camp in Covington, Tennessee.

197
00:26:21,331 --> 00:26:24,918
Camp Freedom Falls. You never forgave her.

198
00:26:25,002 --> 00:26:28,046
Well… It was a terrible experience for you.

199
00:26:28,964 --> 00:26:33,260
The counselors there were some-- Some of the worst people I have ever known.

200
00:26:34,386 --> 00:26:36,513
And they smiled all the time.
Just like you.

201
00:26:36,597 --> 00:26:41,560
We're sorry, Carol. As for us,
we love and accept all beings equally.

202
00:26:41,643 --> 00:26:46,190
Okay. If you're so accepting, then what
about what you're trying to do to me now?

203
00:26:46,273 --> 00:26:49,026
Make me just like you.
Even though you know I do not want that.

204
00:26:49,109 --> 00:26:51,195
You want to change us too, don't you?

205
00:26:51,278 --> 00:26:53,739
- [scoffs]
- Didn't you just ask if it's possible?

206
00:26:55,115 --> 00:26:56,909
There is something else to consider.

207
00:26:57,993 --> 00:27:00,120
We know what it feels like to be you.

208
00:27:01,246 --> 00:27:04,499
To be alone. To suffer. We've been you.

209
00:27:05,501 --> 00:27:07,336
But you've never been us.

210
00:28:39,136 --> 00:28:41,013
- Everything all right, Carol?
- Yeah.

211
00:28:41,096 --> 00:28:42,598
Can we help you find something?

212
00:28:42,681 --> 00:28:45,642
Um… Do you have any heroin?

213
00:28:47,895 --> 00:28:51,231
Are you sure that's a good idea?
Remember last time?

214
00:28:52,482 --> 00:28:54,610
What can I say? Sophomore year was tough.

215
00:28:55,652 --> 00:28:57,654
Course it doesn't hold
a candle to this shit.

216
00:28:57,738 --> 00:29:02,993
Carol, you should know.
We have a whole wing of bodies here recovering from physical addiction.

217
00:29:03,076 --> 00:29:04,828
Some might not make it.

218
00:29:05,704 --> 00:29:07,998
Just… food for thought.

219
00:29:08,081 --> 00:29:09,750
What are you, my nana?

220
00:29:09,833 --> 00:29:12,419
Yesterday, you people gave me
a hand grenade.

221
00:29:12,503 --> 00:29:14,922
Are you seriously gonna
begrudge me some H?

222
00:29:15,005 --> 00:29:17,925
Unfortunately,
this hospital doesn't stock heroin.

223
00:29:18,008 --> 00:29:20,135
We have other opioids.

224
00:29:20,219 --> 00:29:23,722
Ones that were manufactured
under more regulated conditions.

225
00:29:23,805 --> 00:29:25,516
Would oxycodone suffice?

226
00:29:27,768 --> 00:29:31,063
The closest unadulterated heroin is
eight miles from here.

227
00:29:32,272 --> 00:29:33,273
It's on its way.

228
00:29:34,107 --> 00:29:37,569
See? Put your mind to it,
and you guys are better than Domino's.

229
00:29:39,238 --> 00:29:41,365
Where are the hypodermic needles?

230
00:29:41,448 --> 00:29:44,743
Oh, might we suggest snorting
the heroin instead?

231
00:29:44,826 --> 00:29:46,870
It's been quite a number of years
since you've injected.

232
00:29:46,954 --> 00:29:49,289
No. In for a penny, in for a pound.

233
00:29:49,373 --> 00:29:52,960
I'm gonna Sid Vicious this shit
like it's the Chelsea fucking Hotel.

234
00:32:24,027 --> 00:32:25,237
[clears throat]

235
00:32:42,296 --> 00:32:44,298
[snores]

236
00:32:52,681 --> 00:32:53,682
[grunts]

237
00:32:55,767 --> 00:32:56,768
[snores]

238
00:33:24,338 --> 00:33:25,339
[grunts]

239
00:33:33,222 --> 00:33:34,223
[clears throat]

240
00:33:44,441 --> 00:33:45,692
[sighs]

241
00:33:52,658 --> 00:33:53,992
It's just, um…

242
00:33:55,661 --> 00:33:56,662
[blows raspberry]

243
00:33:56,745 --> 00:33:58,247
It's absolutely ineffectious.

244
00:33:59,456 --> 00:34:01,667
- Ineffecti…
- What?

245
00:34:01,750 --> 00:34:05,420
This just, um… This shit does not work.

246
00:34:11,426 --> 00:34:13,679
[speaks indistinctly, stammers]
I'm on my own.

247
00:34:23,981 --> 00:34:25,190
[sobbing]

248
00:34:28,652 --> 00:34:33,574
I miss you. I miss you.
I miss you. I miss you.

249
00:34:44,668 --> 00:34:48,380
[hisses] "'Don't', it said.

250
00:34:48,463 --> 00:34:54,178
Dark slipsand falling from his clothing,
a shadowy figure."

251
00:34:55,012 --> 00:34:56,638
I think this could be a movie.

252
00:34:57,681 --> 00:35:03,020
"She slowly turned to face
the raspy voice."

253
00:35:11,028 --> 00:35:15,157
[whispers] Listen. I'm not that bad.

254
00:35:26,043 --> 00:35:32,174
And that fuckin'… lady… lady pirate they sent, hmm?

255
00:35:32,257 --> 00:35:35,886
Raban. I'm… Oh, I'm sorry. I mean Zosia.

256
00:35:35,969 --> 00:35:39,556
It's Zosia. Oh, you didn't catch her name
because I knew her name. Zosia.

257
00:35:39,640 --> 00:35:40,891
You're a fucking idiot.

258
00:35:40,974 --> 00:35:41,975
Whatever.

259
00:35:42,935 --> 00:35:44,811
How annoying is that chick.

260
00:35:47,689 --> 00:35:51,318
Very, very fucking annoying. All smiley.

261
00:35:51,401 --> 00:35:56,782
"Um, hey. Oh, Hi. Hey, Carol, we just…
we just wanna make you happy.

262
00:35:56,865 --> 00:35:58,909
Blah, blah, blah." [grunts]

263
00:36:00,077 --> 00:36:05,582
She's like. "Oh, oh. We're the whole
wide world, and we're stoked.

264
00:36:06,291 --> 00:36:13,298
It's just life is one big,
long sunshiny walk in the park when you're one of us. Whoo."

265
00:36:14,716 --> 00:36:21,723
No way. Nobody sane is that happy.
I call… [singsongy] …bullshit on that.

266
00:36:24,726 --> 00:36:28,981
And why she gotta be so goddamn fuckable?

267
00:36:34,611 --> 00:36:36,071
[clears throat]

268
00:36:46,665 --> 00:36:47,666
[huffs]

269
00:36:53,463 --> 00:36:56,091
[sighs] We have a winner.

270
00:37:10,314 --> 00:37:11,315
Hey, Carol.

271
00:37:40,302 --> 00:37:41,512
Carol.

272
00:37:42,054 --> 00:37:43,180
Hey.

273
00:37:44,598 --> 00:37:48,602
You look, uh… Yeah.

274
00:37:48,685 --> 00:37:51,313
Got a lot more color in your face.

275
00:37:51,396 --> 00:37:52,898
Thank you.

276
00:37:52,981 --> 00:37:54,274
We feel much better today.

277
00:37:54,358 --> 00:37:58,153
Good. That's good.
How about some fresh air?

278
00:38:02,741 --> 00:38:04,034
How was the heroin?

279
00:38:04,117 --> 00:38:05,369
Uh, I threw it away.

280
00:38:05,452 --> 00:38:06,453
Oh.

281
00:38:06,537 --> 00:38:08,372
Yeah. I wasn't in the mood.

282
00:38:09,915 --> 00:38:11,458
Well, chickened out, actually.

283
00:38:12,251 --> 00:38:13,293
Maybe for the best.

284
00:38:32,980 --> 00:38:37,901
So, uh… when do they let you out of here?

285
00:38:38,610 --> 00:38:41,405
I mean, when do you let you out of here?

286
00:38:42,239 --> 00:38:46,285
Probably in a day or two.
Sooner if we need an extra bed.

287
00:38:46,368 --> 00:38:48,996
Huh, that's great.

288
00:38:49,079 --> 00:38:52,416
Hey, you know everything.

289
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:55,627
Whatever happened to music in elevators?

290
00:38:56,503 --> 00:38:58,505
Huh? When did they stop doing that?

291
00:38:58,589 --> 00:39:00,257
Oh, would you like some?

292
00:39:00,340 --> 00:39:01,633
Sure.

293
00:39:03,510 --> 00:39:04,970
[upbeat music plays]

294
00:39:17,524 --> 00:39:18,942
Nice day.

295
00:39:19,026 --> 00:39:22,237
It is. Thank you for bringing us outside.

296
00:39:22,321 --> 00:39:25,324
Well, I know how much
it sucks being in hospitals.

297
00:39:26,491 --> 00:39:30,621
Better out here, right? Little… Little sunshine?

298
00:39:36,877 --> 00:39:39,546
Really, really nice.

299
00:39:44,510 --> 00:39:49,848
What do you think the temperature is?
About… 80?

300
00:39:49,932 --> 00:39:55,896
Well, It's currently 27.778
degrees Celsius, or 82 degrees Fahrenheit.

301
00:39:56,855 --> 00:40:04,071
The winds are three kilometers
per hour from, uh… - Uh… - From where?

302
00:40:05,364 --> 00:40:13,330
Ah. From south… south-east… - [grunts] - Any chance of precipitation?

303
00:40:14,873 --> 00:40:20,295
[stammers] Percec… Zosia, you with me? I need you to answer some more questions, okay?

304
00:40:21,755 --> 00:40:22,840
Mmm.

305
00:40:22,923 --> 00:40:27,344
How do I reverse all this?
How do I reverse the joining?

306
00:40:28,554 --> 00:40:29,805
No.

307
00:40:29,888 --> 00:40:35,769
Zosia, how do I end this thing?
You… You already told me it's possible.

308
00:40:35,853 --> 00:40:37,604
- [stammers] We… no.
- Yes.

309
00:40:39,523 --> 00:40:43,485
- Yes. Yes. You did. You pretty much did.
- No. No. [stammers]

310
00:40:43,569 --> 00:40:45,821
So, the hard part's over, right?

311
00:40:45,904 --> 00:40:51,201
Now, all you have to do is tell me how to
put things back the way they used to be.

312
00:40:51,285 --> 00:40:53,912
Come on. Tell me, tell me. Come on, Zosia.

313
00:40:54,788 --> 00:40:57,457
Is it making you sad
not giving me what I want?

314
00:40:57,541 --> 00:41:00,711
Is this making you sad? Don't be sad.

315
00:41:00,794 --> 00:41:02,963
Tell me what I want to know.

316
00:41:04,631 --> 00:41:05,632
Uh.

317
00:41:09,011 --> 00:41:11,638
[breathing shakily]

318
00:41:21,064 --> 00:41:22,191
Oh, yeah.

319
00:41:22,691 --> 00:41:24,610
[breathes shakily]

320
00:41:24,693 --> 00:41:27,154
Zosia, Zosia.

321
00:41:28,655 --> 00:41:33,118
Is there something I can do?
Is it something one person can do?

322
00:41:33,202 --> 00:41:36,705
No, stop! Stop! Let go of her.

323
00:41:38,457 --> 00:41:39,958
You can't touch me.

324
00:41:40,542 --> 00:41:42,920
[stutters] I have agency!

325
00:41:43,879 --> 00:41:46,298
I have agency, and you can not interfere!

326
00:41:48,175 --> 00:41:49,718
Back away from us!

327
00:41:52,971 --> 00:41:54,223
[breathes shakily]

328
00:42:02,606 --> 00:42:07,236
Zosia, Zosia. What is it?

329
00:42:07,945 --> 00:42:11,865
Zosia, tell me what it… [grunts]
Is it… Is it some kind of chemical?

330
00:42:11,949 --> 00:42:15,827
[stammers] Some kind of medicine?
Zosia, tell me what it is!

331
00:42:15,911 --> 00:42:31,844
[others chanting] Please, Carol.
Please, Carol. Please, Carol. Please… Zosia, tell me.

332
00:42:33,804 --> 00:42:35,305
Tell me!

333
00:42:36,598 --> 00:42:39,434
What is it? Tell me.

334
00:42:39,518 --> 00:42:41,311
[chanting intensifies]

335
00:42:41,395 --> 00:42:43,105
[Carol] Tell me what it is.

336
00:42:44,147 --> 00:42:47,234
Tell me. Tell me!

337
00:42:50,320 --> 00:42:51,572
[chanting stops]

338
00:42:52,614 --> 00:42:54,241
What… What's happening?

339
00:42:54,324 --> 00:42:57,911
She's dying, Carol.
She's in cardiac arrest.

340
00:42:59,037 --> 00:43:00,038
May we save her?

341
00:43:01,081 --> 00:43:02,332
Yeah.

342
00:43:03,709 --> 00:43:04,835
Excuse us, Carol.

343
00:43:15,679 --> 00:43:17,514
[breathing shakily]

344
00:43:17,598 --> 00:43:19,766
[other panting]

345
00:43:31,904 --> 00:43:33,238
[AED beeps]

346
00:43:34,489 --> 00:43:37,701
[electronic voice] Analyzing. Analyzing.

347
00:43:38,619 --> 00:43:41,705
Shock advised. Stay clear of pa…
